2966-4049	Improve interagency emergency planning	2009-05-23 00:00:00	Commonly, at federal emergency exercises, one finds that some agency representatives have mistaken perceptions of the emergency roles and procedures of other agencies. The national response plan is helpful in that regard, but provides inadequate detail. Potential disconnects should be addressed in the planning process, not during an emergency. There are two ways to address the problem:<br /><br />1) Allow each federal agency to review the emergency plans of other federal agencies. Then, in the plan revision process, agencies can see how their plans need revision in order to mesh with those of the other agencies. <br /><br />2) The federal agencies could establish a plan review team, with representatives from each agency, to review the plans for disconnects and set up meetings with other agency representatives to resolve the disconnects.<br /><br /> <br /><br />Why Is This Idea Important?<br /><br /><div></div><br />	lewisplan	11	12	1	1	http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/dtd/2966-4049	
